WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.080
Imagine, if you will, that you've just been handed a historical text.

00:05.300 --> 00:05.640
Okay.

00:05.880 --> 00:07.160
But not just any text, right?

00:07.200 --> 00:08.900
Like the ultimate historical record.

00:09.020 --> 00:09.280
Right, yeah.

00:09.340 --> 00:13.060
The foundational document that explains exactly where you came from,

00:13.180 --> 00:15.040
how your entire world was built.

00:15.280 --> 00:19.880
Just the absolute unvarnished truth of your cosmic origin.

00:19.900 --> 00:21.260
That sounds like quite the book.

00:21.340 --> 00:22.880
Right, and you're holding it in your hands.

00:23.280 --> 00:24.080
But there is a catch.

00:24.560 --> 00:27.020
And it's a terrifying one.

00:27.040 --> 00:27.860
Of course there is.

00:28.140 --> 00:28.540
Naturally.

00:28.900 --> 00:32.300
This text has been physically designed to be almost impossible to read.

00:32.560 --> 00:36.780
And worse than that, the very act of reading it, the passage of time itself,

00:37.100 --> 00:39.780
really actively erases the words on the page.

00:39.920 --> 00:40.500
Wow, okay.

00:40.620 --> 00:41.760
So it's destroying itself.

00:41.900 --> 00:42.320
Exactly.

00:42.740 --> 00:45.420
The more people who have interacted with this book,

00:45.480 --> 00:47.380
the more the original story has been scrubbed away.

00:47.380 --> 00:53.160
It gets crossed out, replaced with entirely new, confusing, overlapping sentences.

00:53.600 --> 00:55.480
It is a profound paradox, honestly.

00:55.480 --> 01:00.420
I mean, the idea that the most critical information in existence is inherently self-destructing.

01:00.560 --> 01:00.660
Yeah.

01:00.920 --> 01:04.240
And, you know, your first instinct would probably be to just look for a pristine copyright.

01:04.480 --> 01:04.680
Yep.

01:04.680 --> 01:07.100
Like a version of the book that no one has ever touched.

01:07.320 --> 01:10.440
But the universe sets up an even more diabolical trap.

01:10.540 --> 01:11.320
It usually does.

01:11.440 --> 01:12.260
It really does.

01:12.260 --> 01:19.040
The system is engineered so that the only copies that haven't been erased are completely invisible to you in the dark.

01:19.420 --> 01:22.000
The only way you can see a text is if it's glowing.

01:22.640 --> 01:27.840
But the mechanism that makes it glow is the exact same mechanism that destroys the original word.

01:27.980 --> 01:28.080
Right.

01:28.180 --> 01:31.360
So you're left hoping against hope for a miracle, basically.

01:31.360 --> 01:31.860
How much?

01:31.860 --> 01:41.160
You're looking for a completely dark, unread book just floating in an infinite black void that just happens to have a random magnifying glass passing in front of it.

01:41.220 --> 01:41.620
Yes.

01:41.900 --> 01:46.600
Catching a stray beam of light to illuminate a single perfectly preserved page.

01:46.960 --> 01:52.160
And that cosmic miracle, that exact impossible scenario, is what we are exploring today.

01:52.720 --> 01:54.300
Welcome to our deep dive.

01:54.440 --> 01:55.040
Glad to be here.

01:55.140 --> 01:57.380
We are exploring the universe's memory today.

01:57.500 --> 02:00.100
Like, how does the cosmos actually store its history?

02:00.100 --> 02:11.480
And to answer this, we are digging into a truly captivating 2026 paper by independent researcher Fliction, and it's titled Fossil Manifolds and Mediated Extraction.

02:11.660 --> 02:13.420
It's a brilliant piece of work.

02:13.700 --> 02:13.920
Truly.

02:14.000 --> 02:14.760
It really is.

02:14.920 --> 02:22.800
Our mission today is to unpack a profoundly counterintuitive idea, which is that cosmic evolution is actually a massive process of destruction.

02:23.060 --> 02:23.360
Yes.

02:23.360 --> 02:39.360
We're going to figure out how one specific, incredibly faint early universe galaxy named LAP-1B managed to survive this destruction, and why finding the ultimate truths of the cosmos requires just a near impossible set of coincidences.

02:40.120 --> 02:41.000
It's a wild story.

02:41.060 --> 02:43.080
So to start us off, set the stage for us.

02:43.540 --> 02:47.660
What exactly is LAP-1B, and, you know, how did we even find it?

02:47.660 --> 02:54.700
Well, to really grasp the significance of LAP-1B, you have to appreciate the sheer extremes of its physical reality.

02:54.820 --> 02:57.760
I mean, this isn't a galaxy you could just spot with a backyard telescope.

02:57.960 --> 02:58.160
Right.

02:58.320 --> 03:03.760
It was discovered by the James Webb Space Telescope, the JWST, and it sits at an extreme distance.

03:04.240 --> 03:08.260
Specifically, it was observed at a spectroscopic redshift of roughly 6.6.

03:08.340 --> 03:08.680
Okay.

03:08.680 --> 03:15.340
So when we translate that into cosmic time, we are looking at an object as it existed roughly 800 million years after the Big Bang.

03:15.580 --> 03:22.240
Okay, let's unpack this for a second, because that redshift number is just so fundamental to everything we're going to discuss today.

03:22.400 --> 03:23.000
It really is.

03:23.040 --> 03:32.340
Because when we throw around phrases like 800 million years after the Big Bang, we need to remember what astronomy fundamentally is.

03:32.420 --> 03:35.800
We are not looking at LAP-1B right now in the present day.

03:36.080 --> 03:36.760
Far from it.

03:36.760 --> 03:43.140
And Klitschner makes a very specific point to ground the entire paper in this reality.

03:43.540 --> 03:47.660
Astronomy is, at its core, the study of delayed observability.

03:47.740 --> 03:50.020
Oh, I really love that phrase, delayed observability.

03:50.120 --> 03:50.300
Yeah.

03:50.480 --> 03:54.900
Because it reminds you that looking through a telescope is literally looking backward in time.

03:55.300 --> 03:59.460
The light from LAP-1B left those stars over 13 billion years ago.

03:59.540 --> 03:59.960
Exactly.

03:59.960 --> 04:11.600
It traveled across the expanding void of space, which is, you know, why the light waves were stretched out or redshifted into the infrared spectrum, which the JWST is specially designed to capture with those big gold mirrors.

04:11.860 --> 04:11.940
Right.

04:12.060 --> 04:14.900
The universe is expanding, so the light physically stretches.

04:14.900 --> 04:15.580
Yeah.

04:15.920 --> 04:24.780
So the data we downloaded in 2026 represents the exact condition of this galaxy at the moment those photons were emitted, 13 billion years in the past.

04:24.860 --> 04:24.980
Yes.

04:25.240 --> 04:32.720
The galaxy itself has almost certainly completely transformed, like it's been ripped apart or swallowed by something much larger in the intervening eons.

04:33.060 --> 04:34.560
We're studying a ghost.

04:34.560 --> 04:37.260
A ghost, yeah, a temporally displaced projection.

04:37.520 --> 04:38.040
Exactly.

04:38.520 --> 04:43.220
And the anatomy of this particular ghost is just completely baffling.

04:43.360 --> 04:43.820
How so?

04:44.120 --> 04:52.400
Well, we typically judge a galaxy by its mass, specifically its stellar mass, which is the total weight of all the luminous stars inside it.

04:52.620 --> 04:56.360
And the stellar mass of LAP-1B is staggeringly low.

04:56.820 --> 05:00.040
We are talking about less than 3,300 solar masses.

05:00.300 --> 05:01.040
Wait, hold on.

05:01.040 --> 05:06.260
Just 3,300 solar masses, as in the equivalent of 3,300 of our suns.

05:06.280 --> 05:06.700
That's it.

05:06.820 --> 05:07.560
That's the whole thing.

05:07.680 --> 05:07.960
Wow.

05:08.160 --> 05:13.860
To put that into perspective for you, our Milky Way galaxy contains somewhere between 100 billion and 400 billion stars.

05:13.980 --> 05:15.520
So 3,300 is nothing.

05:15.860 --> 05:16.820
It's a rounding error.

05:17.320 --> 05:24.600
It's a quantity of mass you would typically find in a single, small, localized star cluster just floating inside a normal galaxy.

05:24.600 --> 05:31.600
It is incredibly strange to find an entire isolated galactic system weighing so little.

05:31.840 --> 05:36.160
It's like a heavyweight, lightweight, just a tiny handful of stars, gravitationally speaking.

05:36.420 --> 05:36.660
Right.

05:37.120 --> 05:40.640
But the mystery deepens when you look at how those stars are actually moving.

05:40.800 --> 05:41.060
Okay.

05:41.160 --> 05:43.340
By observing the gravitational dynamics.

05:43.460 --> 05:43.640
Yeah.

05:43.640 --> 05:50.780
So how the gas and stars are physically moving and rotating astronomers can calculate the total mass of the entire system.

05:50.960 --> 05:51.140
Right.

05:51.220 --> 05:53.320
Because gravity affects everything around it.

05:53.440 --> 05:53.840
Exactly.

05:54.280 --> 05:59.620
And the dynamical mass of LAP-1B is inferred to be on the order of 10 million solar masses.

06:00.020 --> 06:00.240
Wait.

06:00.360 --> 06:00.520
Okay.

06:00.600 --> 06:04.540
So the gravity holding this whole system together is generated by 10 million solar masses.

06:04.540 --> 06:04.780
Yes.

06:04.780 --> 06:09.260
But the glowing stars we can actually see only account for 3,300 of that.

06:09.580 --> 06:10.040
You got it.

06:10.240 --> 06:16.720
That means the visible, normal matter, the baryonic matter, right, makes up less than 1% of the entire structure.

06:17.200 --> 06:18.580
Significantly less than 1%, yeah.

06:19.040 --> 06:26.000
The luminous component is an absolute afterthought compared to the massive, invisible, dark matter halo it sits inside.

06:26.300 --> 06:30.100
It is one of the most extreme mass discrepancies ever recorded.

06:30.300 --> 06:31.540
That is just wild.

06:31.540 --> 06:34.420
So we have a tiny, faint ghost of a star cluster.

06:34.780 --> 06:39.460
Floating inside a massive, invisible envelope of dark matter near the dawn of time.

06:39.600 --> 06:40.260
That's the setup.

06:41.020 --> 06:46.120
But why does this bizarre setup make it the ultimate historical record we talked about earlier?

06:46.300 --> 06:49.660
Like, why is this specific, weird galaxy so important?

06:50.080 --> 06:54.840
To understand that, we have to completely rethink what it means for a galaxy to evolve.

06:55.160 --> 06:55.380
Okay.

06:55.580 --> 06:58.800
Usually when we hear the word evolution, you know, we think of progress.

06:58.980 --> 07:03.920
Like, a biological organism evolves to become more complex, more adapted, more capable.

07:03.920 --> 07:05.140
Right, getting better over time.

07:05.280 --> 07:06.960
That is the assumption we bring to the table.

07:07.100 --> 07:07.320
Yeah.

07:07.560 --> 07:15.680
But in astrophysics, and specifically within the framework Flixson establishes in this paper, evolution is essentially the erasure of history.

07:15.900 --> 07:16.980
The erasure of history.

07:17.040 --> 07:17.320
Yes.

07:17.560 --> 07:22.680
Flixson introduces a concept called Principle 1, the informational privilege of low averaging systems.

07:22.680 --> 07:23.320
Okay.

07:23.580 --> 07:26.540
The informational privilege of low averaging systems.

07:27.740 --> 07:28.540
That's a mouthful.

07:28.860 --> 07:29.260
It is.

07:29.440 --> 07:35.000
But to understand this, we just have to look at what actually happens inside a normal galaxy as it ages.

07:35.480 --> 07:36.860
We call it chemical evolution.

07:37.700 --> 07:42.640
But Flixson argues a far more accurate term is actually chemical averaging.

07:42.860 --> 07:43.580
Chemical averaging.

07:43.580 --> 07:43.840
Okay.

07:43.920 --> 07:45.940
What exactly is getting averaged here?

07:45.940 --> 07:49.560
Well, think about the life cycle of a galaxy like our Milky Way.

07:50.140 --> 07:51.420
A cloud of gas collapses.

07:51.680 --> 07:52.480
Stars are born.

07:53.080 --> 07:57.060
The most massive of those stars live very short, violent lives.

07:57.140 --> 07:57.320
Right.

07:57.420 --> 07:58.260
They burn out fast.

07:58.320 --> 08:00.900
And when they die, they detonate in supernova explosions.

08:01.560 --> 08:03.780
Now, these explosions are the forges of the universe.

08:03.960 --> 08:07.240
They create heavy elements like oxygen, carbon, silicon, iron.

08:07.380 --> 08:07.980
All the good stuff.

08:08.100 --> 08:09.240
All the stuff we're made of.

08:09.240 --> 08:14.660
And those elements are violently ejected outward, slamming into the surrounding interstellar gas.

08:15.280 --> 08:16.700
That gas is now enriched.

08:17.060 --> 08:21.380
It eventually cools, collapses again, and forms a second generation of stars.

08:21.560 --> 08:21.960
Got it.

08:22.040 --> 08:23.900
And those stars now have a different chemical makeup.

08:24.080 --> 08:27.960
Then they die, they explode, and they inject even more complex elements.

08:28.080 --> 08:30.520
And this cycle repeats for billions of years.

08:30.840 --> 08:33.780
It sounds like a massive chaotic mixing bowl.

08:33.860 --> 08:35.080
It is absolute chaos.

08:35.480 --> 08:37.180
And it's not just stars exploding either.

08:37.180 --> 08:43.100
You have pristine gas constantly flowing into the galaxy from deep space, which dilutes the metals.

08:43.660 --> 08:46.700
You have other dwarf galaxies crashing into the main galaxy,

08:47.140 --> 08:51.720
bringing entirely different populations of stars with completely different chemical histories.

08:51.920 --> 08:52.060
Right.

08:52.140 --> 08:53.340
So it's all just mashing together.

08:53.520 --> 08:53.900
Exactly.

08:54.540 --> 08:58.720
You have enormous kinetic turbulence constantly stirring the interstellar medium.

08:58.720 --> 09:10.440
The cumulative effect of all this is that the gas inside a mature galaxy does not encode the story of any single specific supernova from the early universe.

09:10.680 --> 09:11.540
Ah, I see.

09:11.680 --> 09:19.020
It encodes a massive muddled mathematical average of millions upon millions of different explosive events.

09:19.020 --> 09:21.700
I picture this exactly like mixing paint on a palette.

09:21.860 --> 09:23.300
Oh, that's a great way to think about it.

09:23.380 --> 09:28.940
Like imagine you're an art historian trying to figure out the exact specific colors a painter used on their very first day of work.

09:29.040 --> 09:29.200
Right.

09:29.340 --> 09:33.460
If they just mixed a primary red and a primary blue, you get a distinct purple.

09:33.780 --> 09:37.880
You can look at that purple, analyze it, and easily deduce the original two colors.

09:38.240 --> 09:38.960
Simple enough.

09:38.960 --> 09:41.060
But what if they spent 10 years mixing?

09:41.520 --> 09:50.400
They take a thousand different colors, neon greens, deep ochres, sharp magentas, soft ceruleans, and they just mix them all together in a massive bucket.

09:50.500 --> 09:51.200
You're going to get a mess.

09:51.260 --> 09:53.660
You get a muddy, indistinct brown.

09:54.060 --> 09:59.400
And no matter how closely you look at that muddy brown paint, no matter how powerful your microscope is,

09:59.600 --> 10:06.040
you can never, ever extract the exact shade of the original red that went into the bucket on day one.

10:06.120 --> 10:06.400
Never.

10:06.400 --> 10:11.780
The physical history of that red paints have been chemically averaged out of existence.

10:12.160 --> 10:13.740
That is a phenomenal analogy.

10:14.120 --> 10:17.580
The mature modern galaxy is the bucket of muddy brown paint.

10:17.900 --> 10:20.540
It possesses very high chemical complexity.

10:20.820 --> 10:24.020
You know, there are a lot of different elements on the periodic table floating around in there.

10:24.180 --> 10:27.380
But it has extremely low historical resolution.

10:27.680 --> 10:29.140
Low historical resolution.

10:29.440 --> 10:29.600
Yeah.

10:29.620 --> 10:30.620
Because it's all blended.

10:30.900 --> 10:31.200
Right.

10:31.480 --> 10:33.220
You cannot trace the trajectory backward.

10:33.220 --> 10:39.780
You cannot reconstruct the initial conditions of the universe from a system that has thoroughly scrambled its own data.

10:39.980 --> 10:40.560
Wait, hold on.

10:41.120 --> 10:48.420
If I'm an astronomer trying to map the universe, my first instinct is to put my telescope at the biggest, brightest, most evolved galaxy I can find.

10:48.480 --> 10:48.820
Naturally.

10:48.820 --> 10:52.960
Because wouldn't a massive galaxy give us way more data to work with?

10:53.280 --> 10:58.160
Like, it has more stars emitting light, more gas to run our spectrometers over.

10:58.540 --> 11:03.040
Doesn't more data automatically equal a better understanding of the universe's history?

11:03.260 --> 11:08.080
What's fascinating here is how often we conflate data with historical information.

11:08.260 --> 11:08.660
Oh.

11:08.660 --> 11:13.860
More data in a massive, mature galaxy just means more noise.

11:14.420 --> 11:20.900
You are getting an incredibly detailed, high-resolution picture of the current state of the muddy brown paint.

11:21.020 --> 11:22.320
You know exactly how brown it is.

11:22.480 --> 11:22.860
Exactly.

11:23.220 --> 11:24.360
Exactly what it looks like today.

11:24.860 --> 11:28.380
But you are getting zero information about the initial primary colors.

11:28.980 --> 11:34.400
Fliction draws a crucial distinction here between a galaxy having antiquity and a galaxy being least overwritten.

11:34.600 --> 11:36.260
Antiquity just meaning it's really old, right?

11:36.280 --> 11:36.680
Yeah, right.

11:36.680 --> 11:41.360
You can find a galaxy that formed very early in the universe, making it ancient.

11:42.140 --> 11:52.440
But if that ancient galaxy has spent the last 10 billion years intensely forming stars, undergoing constant supernovae, and merging with other galaxies, it is completely overwritten.

11:52.640 --> 11:53.040
I see.

11:53.280 --> 12:00.560
Its age is completely irrelevant to our historical understanding because it has erased its own origins thousands of times over.

12:00.860 --> 12:03.020
So just finding old things isn't enough.

12:03.120 --> 12:04.720
We need something that hasn't changed.

12:04.820 --> 12:05.280
Exactly.

12:05.280 --> 12:08.560
We need a system that has undergone almost zero enrichment events.

12:08.800 --> 12:10.000
We need LAP-1B.

12:10.000 --> 12:10.320
Right.

12:10.320 --> 12:14.000
Flitchin categorizes LAP-1B as retaining a first-order record.

12:14.520 --> 12:15.760
It is in an unmixed state.

12:16.200 --> 12:20.520
It has an incredibly high ratio of recoverable event history to total elapsed time.

12:20.980 --> 12:25.460
It is, by definition, the least overwritten type of system in the cosmos.

12:25.460 --> 12:28.520
This reminds me so much of modern information overload.

12:28.520 --> 12:29.040
Oh, yeah.

12:29.040 --> 12:30.640
Just think about your email inbox.

12:30.640 --> 12:39.000
If you go off the grid for a month and come back to 10,000 emails, the core essential messages of your life are completely buried.

12:39.480 --> 12:44.260
You have newsletters, reply-alls, spam, automated alerts.

12:44.380 --> 12:50.040
It's overwhelming, and the important signal is just lost in the muddy brown paint of digital noise.

12:50.040 --> 12:51.700
The dreaded unread count.

12:51.820 --> 12:52.300
Exactly.

12:52.760 --> 13:00.340
But if you open your inbox after a month and there is exactly one email sitting there, that message is perfectly legible.

13:00.420 --> 13:01.980
Right, because there's nothing else to look at.

13:02.260 --> 13:05.820
You can analyze every word of it because there is no competing noise.

13:05.820 --> 13:10.340
LAP-1b is the galaxy with only one email in its inbox.

13:10.680 --> 13:14.480
It hasn't had millions of supernovas spamming its interstellar medium.

13:14.740 --> 13:18.440
It has only had one or two, making the initial message perfectly clear.

13:18.620 --> 13:24.040
And recognizing that brings us to a very uncomfortable reality about our own scientific methods.

13:24.220 --> 13:25.060
Uncomfortable how?

13:25.200 --> 13:30.140
There is a massive structural bias built into our entire astronomical survey infrastructure.

13:30.360 --> 13:31.340
A bias against what?

13:31.500 --> 13:32.900
Against the truth, essentially.

13:33.420 --> 13:34.800
Think about how a telescope functions.

13:34.800 --> 13:36.840
It is a light-gathering bucket.

13:37.360 --> 13:41.480
The brighter an object is, the easier it is for our instruments to detect it.

13:41.640 --> 13:41.720
Sure.

13:41.960 --> 13:42.520
That makes sense.

13:42.760 --> 13:46.740
So our infrastructure is heavily biased toward bright, high-flux sources.

13:47.080 --> 13:48.380
And what makes a galaxy bright?

13:49.000 --> 13:49.740
Lots of stars.

13:50.420 --> 13:51.900
What do lots of stars do?

13:52.040 --> 13:52.760
They explode.

13:53.040 --> 13:53.980
They mix the paint.

13:54.280 --> 13:59.220
They explode, mix the interstellar medium, and create highly averaged, overwritten chemistry.

13:59.800 --> 14:04.520
So we are structurally biased to easily find the most corrupted historical records.

14:04.520 --> 14:11.680
Meanwhile, the objects whose information content is the highest, the pristine, unmixed, least

14:11.680 --> 14:16.960
overwritten galaxies like LAP-1b, are inherently the faintest and hardest things to see in the

14:16.960 --> 14:17.720
entire universe.

14:18.500 --> 14:22.620
The cosmos literally hides its most perfect memories in its darkest corners.

14:22.860 --> 14:27.740
We literally built billion-dollar machines that are inherently blind to the purest information.

14:28.080 --> 14:29.060
That is wild.

14:29.280 --> 14:31.620
It's a tough pill to swallow for observational astronomy.

14:31.620 --> 14:34.840
Okay, so we've established that LAP-1b is the unmixed paint.

14:35.000 --> 14:36.500
It's the inbox with one email.

14:36.620 --> 14:38.280
But what does that one email actually say?

14:38.380 --> 14:38.480
Right.

14:38.520 --> 14:39.080
What's the message?

14:39.380 --> 14:39.600
Yeah.

14:39.680 --> 14:44.280
When we run the spectroscopic data and look at the chemical fingerprint of this specific

14:44.280 --> 14:47.820
galaxy, what exactly is the universe trying to tell us?

14:48.380 --> 14:52.560
Well, to read the email, we have to look at the specific chemical abundances that JWST

14:52.560 --> 14:54.900
captured from LAP-1b's glowing gas.

14:55.440 --> 14:57.260
And the numbers are highly anomalous.

14:57.700 --> 14:58.740
Let's start with its oxygen.

14:58.900 --> 14:59.140
Okay.

14:59.140 --> 15:06.260
The gas phase oxygen abundance of LAP-1b is roughly 4.2 times 10 to the negative third

15:06.260 --> 15:08.000
of our sun's solar abundance.

15:09.000 --> 15:12.360
That is an almost incomprehensibly small number.

15:12.360 --> 15:13.860
It is vanishingly small.

15:14.400 --> 15:19.400
For a long time, astrophysicists assumed there was a metallicity floor in observable galaxies.

15:19.580 --> 15:24.300
Like you wouldn't find anything with less than about 2% of our sun's heavy element abundance.

15:24.480 --> 15:26.120
Because it would all have mixed in by now.

15:26.200 --> 15:26.420
Right.

15:26.600 --> 15:28.740
But LAP-1b crashes right through that floor.

15:28.860 --> 15:30.640
It possesses almost zero oxygen.

15:30.740 --> 15:30.960
Okay.

15:31.160 --> 15:32.140
Almost no oxygen.

15:32.240 --> 15:33.160
What about the rest of its makeup?

15:33.480 --> 15:34.980
This is where the true anomaly lies.

15:35.620 --> 15:41.240
While its oxygen is practically non-existent, its carbon-oxygen ratio, the NMAO ratio is highly

15:41.240 --> 15:41.720
elevated.

15:42.120 --> 15:46.160
The data shows the carbon is one to two times the solar value relative to the oxygen.

15:46.260 --> 15:47.700
That's a massive disparity.

15:48.200 --> 15:48.840
It's huge.

15:48.940 --> 15:54.460
So it has barely any oxygen, but relative to what little it does have, it's bursting with

15:54.460 --> 15:54.840
carbon.

15:55.300 --> 15:56.040
Why is that weird?

15:56.160 --> 15:58.360
Don't stars just make a bunch of different elements randomly?

15:58.660 --> 15:59.640
